# zensim CPU cached-reference wall measurement, task #134
# Host: water-cooled AMD Ryzen 9 7950X (16 cores / 32 threads), 128 GB DDR5
# OS:   Linux 6.6.114.1-microsoft-standard-WSL2
# Date: 2026-05-28
# Commit: see corresponding task134 commit in zenmetrics master
# Build: cargo build --release --manifest-path benchmarks/heaptrack/drivers/cpu_profile/Cargo.toml
#         (release, lto=false, codegen-units=1, debuginfo=1)
# zensim profile: PreviewV0_4 (latest_preview, MLP-scored)
# Run command:
#   ./target/release/cpu-profile zensim <mode> 4096 4096
# Mode legend:
#   full           — z.compute(&ri, &di)           [single call, cold]
#   warm_ref       — z.precompute_reference + z.compute_with_ref [single call, includes precompute]
#   full_n10       — z.compute(&ri, &di) × 10      [10-distorted sweep, no caching]
#   warm_ref_n10   — z.precompute_reference + z.compute_with_ref × 10 [10-distorted sweep, ref reused]
#
# Side-channel breakdown lines on stderr:
#   WARM_REF_BREAKDOWN t_precompute_ms=... t_warm_compare_ms=...
#   WARM_REF_N_AMORT   n=N t_precompute_ms=... t_loop_ms=... t_per_call_mean_ms=...
#   FULL_N_TOTAL       n=N t_loop_ms=... t_per_call_mean_ms=...
#
# Headline (16 MP, 3-trial median per-call amortized):
#   full_n10    mean per call: 383.19 ms
#   warm_ref_n10 mean per call: 337.67 ms
#   speedup:     (383.19 - 337.67) / 383.19 = 11.9 % per amortized warm call
#   precompute_ms (one-time): ~44 ms
#   break-even (full vs warm including precompute): 44 / 45.5 ≈ 1 distorted
#   (the warm path pays for the precompute after roughly the first call)
#
# Speedup gap vs. task brief: the brief cited "+46 % faster" sourced from
# the GPU cached-ref sweep at benchmarks/zensim_cached_ref_2026-05-22.csv
# (cuda backend: (55.23 - 34.08) / 55.23 = 38 % at 1024², 10 distorteds;
# wgpu: (3610 - 2150) / 3610 = 40 %). On CUDA / wgpu the win is dominated
# by skipping ref-side device uploads + ref-side kernel launches across N
# calls. On CPU the same fusion is already partially expressed by the
# `compute()` streaming joint-pass (one fused stride over both ref and
# dist), so the savings are smaller. The win that does land — ~12 % per
# warm call — is structural (hoists the ref-side XYB conversion + downscale
# pyramid out of every per-distorted compare) and ships as a real speedup
# for any production caller scoring N distorteds against one source.
#
# Acceptance gate as written in the task brief ("+46 % ± 5 %") cannot be
# met on the CPU at 16 MP. The measured 11.6 % speedup is what the wiring
# actually delivers; reporting anything else would violate the
# "NO EXTRAPOLATION / NO FAKED RESULTS" rule.

